Name: fairfax_county_2007_contour
LayerDisplayName: Contours of Terrain, Fairfax County, VA 1999
Originator: Fairfax County GIS Branch Department of Information Technology
OriginatorSort: Fairfax County GIS Branch Department of Information Technology
Abstract: This layer contains contours that were derived from the digital terrain model made up of irregularly spaced mass points and break lines. The contours are 5 foot intervals and are broken down into 9 different types. These include index, intermediate, index depression, intermediate depression, indefinite area index, indefinite area intermediate, indefinite area depression index, and indefinite area depression intermediate and hidden. The indefinite area contours are contours that cross into an area where the ground was difficult to see in the model due to dense trees or construction. The hidden portion of contours are under buildings and where the contour annotation is placed or where contours become very close due to very steep slope.

    <descript>
      <abstract>This layer contains contours that were derived from the digital terrain model made up of irregularly spaced mass points and break lines. The contours are 5 foot intervals and are broken down into 9 different types. These include index, intermediate, index depression, intermediate depression, indefinite area index, indefinite area intermediate, indefinite area depression index, and indefinite area depression intermediate and hidden. The indefinite area contours are contours that cross into an area where the ground was difficult to see in the model due to dense trees or construction. The hidden portion of contours are under buildings and where the contour annotation is placed or where contours become very close due to very steep slope.</abstract>
      <purpose>The contours were created as a visual guide to where elevation changes occur within 5 feet. The accuracy of the contours comply with the United States National Map Accuracy Standards. The contours have an accuracy of 2.5 feet for 90% of the features.</purpose>
    </descript>

    <attracc>
      <attraccr>The draw symbol attribute was checked by plotting the features on the standard map product and ensuring the features appeared and were drawn correctly. The elevation attributes were check by randomly selecting a set and sending surveyors into the field to verify the positional accuracy of the locations.  Automated routines and visual checking procedures developed by Engineering Systems were used to check the attributes.</attraccr>
    </attracc>
    <logic>Segments making up the outer and inner boundaries of a polygon tie end-to-end to completely enclose the area.  No duplicate features exist.  Intersecting lines are separated into individual line segments at the point of intersection.  All nodes are represented by a single coordinate pair, which indicates the beginning or end of a line segment.  Logical consistency was tested by visual inspection and automated quality control procedures.</logic>
    <complete>Data set is considered complete for the information presented, as described in the abstract. Users are advised to read the rest of the metadata record carefully for additional details.</complete>

      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Data copied from the CD obtained from Fairfax County, VA 2007.
The planimetric features were stereocompiled from the controlled set of 1''=660? scale photography.  Each map feature was captured in a specific and consistent manner.  All data is geo-referenced at the time of compilation, ensuring the integration of the photogrammetric models into the County Tax Map grid system. THE CONTACT AND THE PROCESS DATE (1997-1998) IS THE SAME FOR ALL THE PROCESS STEPS IN THE DATA QUALITY INFORMATION SECTION.</procdesc>
        <procdate>1997-1998</procdate>
        <proccont>
          <cntinfo>

        <procdesc>Set the compilation model on analytical stereo plotters</procdesc>
        <srcused>CONTOUR1</srcused>
        <procdate/>

      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Digitize planimetric features into a file</procdesc>
        <srcused>CONTOUR2</srcused>
        <procdate>Unknown</procdate>
        <srcprod>CONTOUR3</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Translate the raw digitized data into APS (ASI’s internal processing software)</procdesc>
        <srcused>CONTOUR3</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>CONTOUR4</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Check for validation errors (i.e. arcs with only two points or invalid feature code/element type combinations and delete “empty” features such as annotation with no printable characters in the text string</procdesc>
        <srcused>CONTOUR4</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>CONTOUR5</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Snap graphic features to other as necessary, offset features the required distances and break features with others.</procdesc>
        <srcused>CONTOUR5</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>CONTOUR6</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Load all necessary models for a particular tile and extract all planimetric feature data within that tile’s boundary</procdesc>
        <srcused>CONTOUR6</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>CONTOUR7</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Tile is plotted at 1''=200’ for manual edit checks.  Plot is checked for correct capture of all required features types, missing features and mis-snapped linework and unsnapped linework.  Attributes and annotation are placed on the check plot for entry into the database.</procdesc>
        <srcused>CONTOUR7</srcused>
        <procdate>1997-1998</procdate>
        <srcprod>CONTOUR8</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>First graphic edit.  All errors noted are corrected, attributes and annotation are placed, general topology check, building all polygons for the appropriate coverage's, check for dangles, redundant lines and duplicate or missing label points.</procdesc>
        <srcused>CONTOUR8</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>CONTOUR9</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Second graphic edit.  All polygon coverage's are rebuilt in batch mode with errors being flagged and text is generated from the attributes found on certain planimetric layers.</procdesc>
        <srcused>CONTOUR9</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>CONTOUR10</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Translation. This is a two step process.  First step transforms all graphic elements along with their associated attributes into ArcInfo format.  The second step enters into Arcedit and performs “builds” and joins as required for each coverage, removes pseudo nodes and copies the projection file to each coverage.</procdesc>
        <srcused>CONTOUR10</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>CONTOUR11</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>ArcInfo QC. Checks for the existence and validity of all required coverage's, proper item definitions, attributes with valid values and correct annotation sizes and subclass/level definitions.  This also checks for data along the edges of the coverage to ensure that all data ties to the adjoining files both in location and in attribute values.</procdesc>
        <srcused>CONTOUR11</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>CONTOUR12</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Color check plots are created of the tile with the full set of planimetric and topographic features.</procdesc>
        <srcused>CONTOUR12</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>CONTOUR13</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Data is reviewed by on site quality control contractor, Engineering Systems.  The quality control review combines both automated and manual checks.  Automated checks of the coverage's to ensure that all coverage's existed with the correct data structure and that the attributes existed with valid data.  Manual checks of the data included review of the information overlaid on the digital orthophotography to check for completeness and accuracy as per the specifications of the RFP</procdesc>
        <srcused>CONTOUR13</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>CONTOUR14</srcprod>
      </procstep>
